codex
I would not rubber-stamp the stated root cause as complete.

The `ms_used` accounting fix is correct. D3D9 sets `m_offset` at lock and only advances by actual unlock count: [Direct3d9_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp](/D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d9/src/win32/Direct3d9_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp:217), [Direct3d9_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp](/D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d9/src/win32/Direct3d9_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp:244). Current D3D11 now mirrors that: [Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp](/D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d11/src/win32/Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp:327), [Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp](/D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d11/src/win32/Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData.cpp:458).

But “any mid-frame `WRITE_DISCARD` corrupts already-issued D3D11 draws” is not a valid D3D11 rule. If the draw has actually been submitted, `WRITE_DISCARD`/rename is supposed to protect it. If it corrupts, either the draw was not issued yet, or this renderer later binds the same logical ring object after its contents/generation changed.

The key D3D11-specific bug is likely that the plugin has only one explicit `ID3D11Buffer` for the shared ring, and every dynamic bind re-fetches that global buffer: [Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp](/D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d11/src/win32/Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp:2265), [Direct3d11_VertexBufferVectorData.cpp](/D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d11/src/win32/Direct3d11_VertexBufferVectorData.cpp:143). If engine work prepares dynamic slices before all corresponding draws are submitted, a later discard/reset means old slice metadata still points at “the shared ring”, not the actual backing generation that contained its bytes.

So the minimal correct architecture is:

1. Keep actual-used accounting in `unlock(numberOfVertices)`.
2. Replace the single `ms_d3dRingBuffer` with a small explicit ring of D3D11 buffers/generations.
3. On append, use current generation.
4. On discard/wrap, advance to the next generation, reset `ms_used = 0`, and map that buffer.
5. Store the selected `ID3D11Buffer*` on the `Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData` slice at lock time.
6. Bind `data->getVertexBuffer()` for dynamic VBs, not `Direct3d11_DynamicVertexBufferData::getSharedRingBuffer()`.

That makes a prepared-but-not-yet-drawn slice carry both offset and buffer generation.

`CuiLayerRenderer`’s “lock all remaining, unlock actual” pattern is bad pressure on a shared allocator: [CuiLayerRenderer.cpp](/D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/library/clientUserInterface/src/shared/core/CuiLayerRenderer.cpp:64). It works in D3D9 because D3D9 is the reference and the backend accounting expects it, but for D3D11 I would also cap UI batches to a fixed sane size. Still, capping UI is secondary; it does not solve generation loss on wrap.

If post-fix black triangles happen before any post-fix wrap, then the generation theory is falsified and the next target is the existing overrun detector around [Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp](/D:/Code/swg-client-v2/src/engine/client/application/Direct3d11/src/win32/Direct3d11_StateCache.cpp:3221): prove whether indexed draws are reading outside `ms_currentVBVertexCount`.
